00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:08.000
Now, this set of pictures gives you a sense that cancers progress.  

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:13.000
They progress from early-stage, relatively normal looking tissue  

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:17.000
through much more advanced cancers, including to the point of metastasis.  

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:22.000
And we are beginning to understand this process in some detail both in  

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:27.000
terms of what the cells look like, the tissues look like, but also what  

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:32.000
the genes look like that are driving these processes forward.  

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:35.000
And I'm now going to give you some examples, or introduce the concept,  

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:38.000
that cancer progression from normalcy to malignancy is associated  

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:42.000
with changes in genes. That's really going to be a major  

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:45.000
theme of today and in the following lectures.  But  

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:49.000
histologically, the process looks like this in cartoon form.  

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:52.000
One starts with a normal looking tissue.  All of your cells are  

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:56.000
organized in one way or another in tissues, where they have important  

00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:59.000
interactions with their neighboring cells: so here,  

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:03.000
a series of, say, epithelial cells.  

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:06.000
Maybe these are the cells that line your gut.  They are in normal  

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:10.000
juxtaposition with their neighbors. They are sitting atop what's called  

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:13.000
a basement membrane, proteins that are secreted by those  

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:17.000
cells and other cells to give the cell something literally to sit on  

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:21.000
it, attach to. And then there are other cells in  

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:24.000
their vicinity including the cells that give rise to these cells,  

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:28.000
the stem cells or precursor cells, of the tissue that will be called on  

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:32.000
to differentiate into these end stage cells when these cells are  

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:36.000
lost, sloughed off. At some frequency in all of us,  

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:40.000
alterations occur in these cells such that an abnormal cell arises.  

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:45.000
This is a cell which has acquired a change.  I'll tell you now that it's  

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:50.000
a genetic change which allows that cell to do things that its neighbors  

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:54.000
can't do.  And in particular, it allows those cells to grow,  

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:59.000
to divide inappropriately.  Your tissues are very carefully  

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:04.000
orchestrated systems with the appropriate numbers of cells.  

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:08.000
And cancer is fundamentally a disease of too many cells.  

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:13.000
And so one of the first things to go wrong in the cancer development  

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:17.000
process is this orderly cell division is disrupted such that now,  

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:22.000
too many cells are produced.  And this results in a phenomena known as  

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:27.000
hyperplasia, hyperplasia meaning too many cells.  

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:31.000
But importantly these cells look pretty normal.  

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:35.000
So to the pathologist, and I'll show you some pathology  

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:39.000
slides in a second, to the pathologist, they would say  

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:43.000
the abnormal cells in number have a normal morphology.  

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:47.000
Their shape looks right. Their internal structures look  

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:51.000
right.  Their nuclei look right. This process can continue, and  

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:55.000
probably often does continue until there is a discernible mass at least  

00:09:55.000 --> 00:10:00.000
when it comes to solid tumors, a discernible mass.  

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:03.000
And here we refer to this as an adenoma.  And I'll show you these  

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:06.000
terms again in a minute on the board, in this case, an adenoma,  

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:10.000
a benign tumor.  And you heard that were before, benign,  

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:13.000
as opposed to malignant. And a benign tumor is a tumor in  

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:17.000
the sense that there are too many cells.  So it's a mass.  

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:20.000
But the cells look pretty normal. In a benign tumor, it's not  

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:24.000
considered to be life-threatening. The cells have not undergone  

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:27.000
sufficient changes that we know for sure that they're going to,  

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:31.000
for example, invade and spread throughout the body.  

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:35.000
And oftentimes, benign tumors are left alone because  

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:39.000
they don't have the potential to spread or to become more aggressive.  

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:44.000
But some of them do.  And through additional changes within the cells,  

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:48.000
additional alterations take place such that now the cells really do  

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:53.000
look different from the neighbors. Their structures look different.  

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:57.000
Their overall shape looks different. Their nuclei look different.  Their  

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:02.000
interactions with the neighboring cells look different.  

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:06.000
And the structure of the tissue changes as well in the sense that  

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:11.000
now, new blood vessels have been recruited into this mass,  

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:15.000
which was important actually in feeding this growing tumor.  

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:20.000
This is true cancer.  It's called in C2 cancer because it's present  

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:24.000
at the original site where the process started in C2 cancer.  

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:29.000
And it's called cancer based on these various characteristics: how  

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:33.000
much the cells are growing, dividing, and also what the cells  

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:38.000
look like, their shape and their nuclear shape.  

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:41.000
That's a problem. But it's a bigger problem because  

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:45.000
it facilitates and usually leads to the development of these tumors into  

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:49.000
an invasive state. So now, the cells are no longer  

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:53.000
staying where they started. They are starting to move out into  

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:57.000
the surrounding tissue. They break down, degrade the  

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:01.000
extracellular matrix, and actually start to migrate away  

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:05.000
from the primary tumor into the surrounding tissue,  

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:09.000
into the surrounding musculature, and ultimately into the blood  

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:13.000
vessels. It can move into the blood vessels.  

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:17.000
And once there, they can move throughout the body,  

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:21.000
and escape the blood vessels, and take up residence elsewhere in a  

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:25.000
process known as metastasis. This process happens at some  

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:29.000
frequency once started. If it reaches this point,  

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:33.000
it's a very bad situation.  Most cancers that kill people,  

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:38.000
kill people because of this process of metastasis.  

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:42.000
90% of cancer deaths are attributable to metastasis.  

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:46.000
And although we know many of the things that happened over the course  

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:50.000
of these earlier stages, we actually know this process  

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:54.000
relatively less well. And obviously, we need to  

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:58.000
understand it better if we are going to control mortalities  

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:01.000
due to cancer. This shows you some histology.  

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:05.000
These are slices through tumors and other tissue that a pathologist  

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:09.000
would look at, and kind of emphasizes the points  

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:13.000
that I was making on an earlier slide in cartoon form.  

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:16.000
So, here you have a lung. And in it is some abnormal cells in  

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:20.000
the red circle here. There are too many cells compared  

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:24.000
to the surrounding tissue. You can see them in this kind of  

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:28.000
dark blue depiction. And you'll see it easier on your  

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:31.000
computer screens later. But again, these cells look  

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:35.000
relatively normal. There are just too many of them.  

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:39.000
So we call this hyperplasia.  These can progress into small and benign  

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:42.000
tumors called, in this case, adenomas.  

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:46.000
And you can see on the histology that they are rather homogeneous in  

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:50.000
their structure. The cytoplasm looks pretty much the  

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:53.000
same.  Cell to cell, the nuclei look pretty much the same  

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:57.000
cell to cell.  And they actually look pretty similar to the normal  

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:01.000
cells that surround them. So this is not true cancer.  

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:04.000
This is a benign tumor. But it can progress to a true  

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:07.000
cancer, adenocarcinomas. And you can see from the high  

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:11.000
magnification view that this looks very different from this.  

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:14.000
The cells don't look the same one to the other, and their nuclei don't  

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:18.000
look the same either. And what you can't appreciate is  

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:21.000
that these cells are also dividing at a much greater rate compared to  

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:24.000
these cells.  And so, this is true cancer.  And this has  

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:28.000
the potential, then, to spread to metastatic  

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:32.000
disease. OK, so I've given you,  

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:37.000
there, all bunch of terminology. Let me tell you a bit more about it.  

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:52.000
 Hyperplasia: too many cells.  

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:56.000
That's all it means.  Hyper: too many.  Plasia: growth,  

00:14:56.000 --> 00:15:03.000
too much growth.   

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:11.000
Hyperplasias can result in benign tumors, which are non-aggressive --  

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:17.000
 -- nondestructive --  

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:23.000
 And they, at this moment at least,  

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:28.000
have not spread to nearby tissue, non-aggressive meaning that the  

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:34.000
cells look pretty normal. They don't look different from  

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:43.000
their normal neighbors.   

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:48.000
These can give rise to malignant tumors.  And the word cancer is  

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:54.000
actually reserved for malignant tumors.  If you have a tumor that's  

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:59.000
benign, you don't have cancer. Cancer refers to malignant tumors.  

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:05.000
And these are different in the sense that they are aggressive.  

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:08.000
The cells are much more active. They've changed their shape.  

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:15.000
They've changed their structures.   

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:18.000
They are destructive, that is, they secrete factors into  

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:22.000
the environment, which break down,  

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:29.000
for example, extracellular matrix.   

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:34.000
And they have the potential to spread.  They've begun to invade  

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:39.000
into the local environment, and can't access the blood supply.  

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:44.000
OK, there are cancers in many of your organs in many different cell  

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:49.000
types within those organs. In the cancers in different places  

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:54.000
in your body are referred to by different terms.  

00:16:54.000 --> 00:17:01.000
 For epithelial tissues,  

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:09.000
skin, intestines, breast, brain, lung, epithelial tissues,  

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:18.000
we call the tumors carcinomas.   

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:23.000
Carcinomas, and depending on the particular cells that are affected,  

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:29.000
whether they are glandular cells or secretory cells,  

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:35.000
we can give them additional names, for example, an adenocarcinoma.  

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:40.000
And that's a cancer that looks like the glands that give rise to the  

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:46.000
tumor in adenocarcinoma. And there could be adenocarcinomas  

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:52.000
in the different places that I mentioned previously.  

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:58.000
And there are benign versions of this tumors.  And for  

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:04.000
adenocarcinomas, the benign version the adenoma.  

