Several children then turning into 20, 30 year olds developed tumors of  

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:27.000
this type which fits to the theme of the lecture in terms of exposures  

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:36.000
leading to cancers.   

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:42.000
Tumors of the blood system are referred to by different  

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:55.000
names, leukemias --   

00:19:55.000 --> 00:20:00.000
-- in which the tumor cells are in the blood, B cell leukemias,  

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:06.000
T cell leukemias, erythroleukemias, myeloid leukemias where the cells  

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:12.000
are in the bloodstream like the one I showed you before,  

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:17.000
and lymphomas where the tumors are in the lymph organs like the spleen  

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:23.000
or the thymus or the lymph nodes. So, that gives you some terminology.  

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:29.000
And I'll be referring to some of this terminology as we go through  

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:35.000
the remaining lectures. And it's just useful to know as you  

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:52.000
learn about and hear about cancers.   

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:56.000
Now, cancer research, over the last several decades has  

00:20:56.000 --> 00:21:01.000
been dedicated to try to understand this process of normalcy to  

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:06.000
malignancy.  How does that happen? And the conclusion from all of this  

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:10.000
work, which I will review for you is that cancer is a genetic disease.  

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:15.000
What do I mean by that?  What do I mean by cancer is a genetic disease?  

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:20.000
Does anybody want to hazard a guess? What do we normally think of when  

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:24.000
we talk about genetic diseases? Heritable diseases, predispositions  

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:29.000
to disease, we talked about several of them previously in the class like  

00:21:29.000 --> 00:21:34.000
cystic fibrosis and many others. Cancer can be a genetic disease in  

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:38.000
that sense.  There can be inherited predispositions to certain cancers.  

00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:42.000
And I'll mention some in later lectures.  But in fact,  

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:46.000
all cancers are genetic diseases. All cancers arise through  

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:50.000
alterations in your genes. Those alterations in most cases are  

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:54.000
not inherited from one of your parents but are acquired through  

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:58.000
your lifetimes through mistakes or exposures to things that  

00:21:58.000 --> 00:22:03.000
cause such changes. Why do we believe this so strongly?  

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:09.000
Well, firstly, and this has been known for some time,  

00:22:09.000 --> 00:22:15.000
cancer cells don't look normal chromosomally.  

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:21.000
If you look at the chromosomes of normal cells, they're all the same.  

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:27.000
All have 46 chromosomes.  The chromosomes have proper structures  

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:34.000
but when you look at cancer cells, that's not true.  

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:37.000
For most cancers, in contrast to the normal karyotype,  

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:40.000
the normal chromosomal number in architecture, and this is an image  

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:44.000
which highlights the different chromosomes by different colors.  

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:47.000
This technique allows us to distinguish one chromosome from the  

00:22:47.000 --> 00:22:51.000
other based on the color that it stains with these dyes that are used  

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:54.000
here.  Anyway, this is a normal cell,  

00:22:54.000 --> 00:22:58.000
46 chromosomes.  And here's a cancer cell.  And it's different  

00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:01.000
in many ways. There are way too many chromosomes.  

00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:05.000
So it's a defect in chromosome number.  But it's also a defect in  

00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:09.000
chromosome structure. And you can see in the boxes a  

00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:13.000
couple of alterations here. There is a chromosome 7, which is  

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:17.000
lacking a little bit of its end. So it's got a truncation.  I think  

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:21.000
that's a seven. Actually, maybe that's not.  

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:25.000
Many that's chromosome 24.  Anyway, it doesn't matter.  And here, you  

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:29.000
can see, it looks like an ice cream cone: a little bit of paint on the  

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:33.000
bottom, a little bit of green on the top.  

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:36.000
This is a new kind of chromosome that has been fused by two different  

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:39.000
chromosomes coming together. So this is a translocation.  And  

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:43.000
here's another translocation here. So, chromosomes and cancer cells  

00:23:43.000 --> 00:23:46.000
are often abnormal in their structure.  They can have  

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:49.000
translocations. They can have deletions.  

00:23:49.000 --> 00:23:53.000
They can have other kinds of rearrangements.  

00:23:53.000 --> 00:23:56.000
And so, based on this, we know that cancer has defects in  

00:23:56.000 --> 00:24:00.000
its genomes, and ultimately we know in its genes.  

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:05.000
We also know that agents that cause cancer --  

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:11.000
 -- and we refer to these  

00:24:11.000 --> 00:24:20.000
as carcinogens --   

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:29.000
-- cancer-causing agents, carcinogens are most often mutagens --  

00:24:29.000 --> 00:24:49.000
 -- agents that cause mutations.  

00:24:49.000 --> 00:24:53.000
Carcinogens are mostly mutagens. And therefore, it's likely that the  

00:24:53.000 --> 00:24:57.000
reason they are carcinogens is because they lead to mutations in  

00:24:57.000 --> 00:25:02.000
cellular genes. We believe that very strongly,  

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:07.000
and it's based on work from many groups over long periods of time  

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:11.000
that have established this kind of correlation.  To sort of prove the  

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:16.000
point, many, many agents, many, many things that have been  

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:21.000
suspected to be cancer-causing have been tested to see whether they are  

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:26.000
mutation causing, to see whether carcinogens are  

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:31.000
mutagens.  And they are tested using assays --  

00:25:31.000 --> 00:25:41.000
 -- like carcinogenicity assays where  

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:46.000
the compound in question or the agent, might be a physical agent  

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:51.000
like radiation, is tested to see whether it will  

00:25:51.000 --> 00:25:56.000
promote tumor formation. And this is typically done in  

00:25:56.000 --> 00:26:01.000
laboratory animals. So, you expose, say,  

00:26:01.000 --> 00:26:06.000
a mouse or a rate to the agents in question, and you ask the question,  

00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:12.000
over time, does that promote the formation of a discernible tumor?  

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:16.000
If yes, then the agent is a carcinogen.  OK,  

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:20.000
and then you ask the question, is the agent a mutagen --  

00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:30.000
 -- using mutagenicity assays.  

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:34.000
And these are typically done in bacteria because they can be done  

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:38.000
very, very rapidly. We can ask whether the agent is  

00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:42.000
able to cause mutations in bacterial cells.  And the standard assay that  

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:46.000
has been developed, and is still in use,  

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:50.000
is to take this agent, drop it into a broth carrying  

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:54.000
bacteria, and not just any bacteria, but bacteria that have mutation in a  

00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:58.000
gene required for histidine synthesis.  

00:26:58.000 --> 00:27:07.000
 They can't make their own histidine,  

00:27:07.000 --> 00:27:11.000
the amino acid histidine.  And so, for them to grow,  

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:16.000
they require histidine in the medium here, or in the medium on the plate,  

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:21.000
the auger plate that you grow them. If you were to take some of these  

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:25.000
histidine minus bacteria, and plate them on a tissue culture  

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:30.000
plate, or rather a bacterial plate, that lacked histidine would any of  

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:35.000
them grow? No, because they can make their own.  

00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:39.000
You have been given them any.  So they can't grow into colonies.  

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:43.000
You would get zero colonies if you did that.  This is due to a mutation  

00:27:43.000 --> 00:27:48.000
in a single gene. If you can create another mutation  

00:27:48.000 --> 00:27:52.000
at that site and revert the abnormal gene into a normal gene,  

00:27:52.000 --> 00:27:57.000
now the cells can make their own histidine.  So,  

00:27:57.000 --> 00:28:01.000
if you can mutate these cells back to becoming competent to make  

00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:05.000
histidine, then if you plate these cells on a histidine minus plate,  

00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:10.000
you might get colonies. You would get some colonies.  

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:14.000
For every bacterial cell that acquired a mutation at the right  

00:28:14.000 --> 00:28:18.000
site, fixing the histidine synthesis gene, now that cell would be able to  

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:22.000
grow into a colony. And actually, the potency of the  

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:26.000
mutagen determines how many colonies you get.  So, you can have weakly  

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:30.000
acting mutagens or strongly acting mutagens.  And  

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:34.000
as I mentioned, most agents that pass this test will also  

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:43.000
pass this test, OK?   

00:28:43.000 --> 00:29:00.000
However --   

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:04.000
-- some known carcinogens fail that test.  They clearly are carcinogens.  

00:29:04.000 --> 00:29:09.000
You paint them on the back of a mouse or feed it to an animal: the  

00:29:09.000 --> 00:29:13.000
animal will develop cancer. And yet, when you do the bacterial  

00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:18.000
reversion test, they don't show up as being mutagens.  

00:29:18.000 --> 00:29:25.000
Why is that so?  Anybody?  Yes?   

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:28.000
They could be so mutagenic that they block the development of the  

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:32.000
bacteria at all. That's actually a very interesting  

00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:36.000
idea, not what I was thinking of. But it's a good idea.  They are  

00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:40.000
super mutagens. So they fail the test for that  

00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:44.000
reason.  Anything else? What's different between this test  

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:48.000
of this mutagenicity, and what actually happens in the  

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:52.000
body?  Anybody? Yes?  That's good.  

00:29:52.000 --> 00:29:56.000
And I'll actually come back to that. There is another good suggestion,  

00:29:56.000 --> 00:30:00.000
but I'll come back to that answer in a second.  

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:05.000
The difference is metabolism. Your body metabolizes things that  

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:10.000
you get exposed to that you eat, or that you inhale, or that you  

00:30:10.000 --> 00:30:16.000
inject yourselves with. It metabolizes it oftentimes to  

00:30:16.000 --> 00:30:21.000
detoxify it or to make it more water-soluble so that you can  

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:27.000
excrete it.  There is a lot of metabolism breaking down or changing  

00:30:27.000 --> 00:30:32.000
the things that you get exposed to. And so, it's been observed that  

00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:37.000
there are certain compounds which are not themselves mutagens but are  

00:30:37.000 --> 00:30:42.000
pro-mutagens.  They have the capacity to turn into mutagens.  

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:47.000
And in the process of metabolic enzymes, they become mutagens.  

00:30:47.000 --> 00:30:52.000
And there are very important carcinogens that fall into this  

00:30:52.000 --> 00:30:57.000
category.  And one of them is shown here.  This is a polycyclic  

00:30:57.000 --> 00:31:02.000
hydrocarbon called benzoate pyrene. It's a very important ingredient in  

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:06.000
cigarette smoke as well as in barbecued beef.  

00:31:06.000 --> 00:31:10.000
It's a very potent carcinogen. It passes this test with flying  

00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:14.000
colors.  But if you do the bacterial reversion test,  

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:19.000
you don't see anything. And the reason is that in the body,  

00:31:19.000 --> 00:31:23.000
many of these double bonds had to be broken and replaced ultimately by  

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:27.000
hydroxyl groups to make this compound more water-soluble so that  

00:31:27.000 --> 00:31:32.000
it can be excreted. And an intermediate step in the  

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:36.000
detoxification, the hydroxylation,  

00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:41.000
is the formation of epoxide. And these epoxides are actually  

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:45.000
highly reactive to DNA. And these molecules, these  

00:31:45.000 --> 00:31:50.000
intermediates, are highly mutagenic.  

00:31:50.000 --> 00:31:55.000
And so, when you make these in your body, thinking you're doing a good  

00:31:55.000 --> 00:31:59.000
thing, you're actually doing a bad thing by creating a mutagen.  

00:31:59.000 --> 00:32:04.000
And it's this that's the mutagenic agent.  And so,  

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:08.000
now the simple bacterial reversion test has been replaced by something  

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:13.000
called the Ames test named after Bruce Ames from Berkeley in which  

00:32:13.000 --> 00:32:18.000
the compound in question is not just given directly to the bacteria.  

00:32:18.000 --> 00:32:23.000
Its first passed through an extract of the liver, usually rat liver,  

00:32:23.000 --> 00:32:28.000
and it's in the liver where these detoxifying enzymes do their job,  

00:32:28.000 --> 00:32:33.000
these cytochrome P450's that are referred to here are present in  

00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:39.000
abundance in your liver. And so if mutagens are going to be  

00:32:39.000 --> 00:32:45.000
formed, they should be formed in this in vitro extract.  

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:52.000
And then, one takes the product of that and performs the bacterial  

00:32:52.000 --> 00:32:58.000
mutation or reversion test. OK, and now the things that were  

00:32:58.000 --> 00:33:04.000
carcinogens but not seen to be mutagens can be seen to be mutagens  

00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:13.000
again.  OK, but --   

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:30.000
-- still --   

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:36.000
There are still some truly non-mutagenic carcinogens.  

00:33:36.000 --> 00:33:42.000
And two examples are alcohol and asbestos.  

00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:48.000
 These do not pass any mutagenicity  

00:33:48.000 --> 00:33:52.000
tests that I'm aware of. But both of them are clearly linked  

00:33:52.000 --> 00:33:56.000
to cancer development: alcohol in the case of liver,  

00:33:56.000 --> 00:34:00.000
cancer, and head and neck cancer, and asbestos in the case of  

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:04.000
mesothelioma, the lining of the lung.  

00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:08.000
So these are not mutagens. So how did they promote cancer  

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:12.000
formation?  Based on the mechanism that was suggested over here.  

00:34:12.000 --> 00:34:17.000
These agents cause irritation in tissues --  

00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:29.000
 -- which results in tissue  

00:34:29.000 --> 00:34:38.000
destruction, loss of cells --   

00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:44.000
-- and their replacement of those cells, cell replenishment.  

00:34:44.000 --> 00:34:50.000
So, it recruits a lot of cells to begin to divide when they normally  

00:34:50.000 --> 00:34:56.000
wouldn't.  So it results in increased proliferation,  

00:34:56.000 --> 00:35:02.000
and the increased potential for mutation because - 

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:07.000
when cells divide. When they duplicate their DNA,  

00:35:07.000 --> 00:35:11.000
there is an inherent risk of making mistakes.  It's not an error-free  

00:35:11.000 --> 00:35:16.000
process.  So the more cell division there is, the more opportunity there  

00:35:16.000 --> 00:35:20.000
is for error, and therefore, the increased risk of acquiring  

00:35:20.000 --> 00:35:25.000
mutations and becoming ultimately a cancer.  OK, I want to take a couple  

00:35:25.000 --> 00:35:29.000
of minutes talking about one really important environmental carcinogen,  

00:35:29.000 --> 00:35:34.000
something that we get exposed to. And that is cigarette smoke.  

00:35:34.000 --> 00:35:39.000
I mentioned that benzoate pyrene is one of the important ingredients in  

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:44.000
cigarette smoke, but it's actually not the only  

00:35:44.000 --> 00:35:49.000
mutagen.  There are actually hundreds of mutagens in cigarette  

00:35:49.000 --> 00:35:55.000
smoke.  And this is the most important environmental carcinogen  

00:35:55.000 --> 00:36:00.000
that we have in our environments. And it results in a large number of  

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:05.000
deaths per year. Tobacco smoke is responsible for a  

00:36:05.000 --> 00:36:10.000
high percentage of the 175, 00 people who die from lung cancer  

00:36:10.000 --> 00:37:35.866
in this country each year. About 150 were either smokers  

00:34:48.000 --> 00:36:27.000
or former smokers.   

00:36:27.000 --> 00:36:31.000
And the association between lung cancer and cigarette smoking is  

00:36:31.000 --> 00:36:35.000
really striking. If you look here,  

00:36:35.000 --> 00:36:40.000
the green line represents cigarette consumption in males from the  

00:36:40.000 --> 00:36:44.000
beginning of the century, the 1900s, through 1960.  And you  

00:36:44.000 --> 00:36:49.000
can see it rapidly increased through availability and social acceptance  

00:36:49.000 --> 00:36:53.000
and social trends. Smoking was really rampant in the  

00:36:53.000 --> 00:36:58.000
society.  And shortly thereafter, with about a 20 year lag, you could  

00:36:58.000 --> 00:37:02.000
see that lung cancer risk increased dramatically as well,  

00:37:02.000 --> 00:37:07.000
which is directly attributable to the cigarette smoke exposure.  

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:10.000
It took time because cancers don't develop right away.  

00:37:10.000 --> 00:37:13.000
They develop over years, and so you need to get exposed to  

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:17.000
stuff over a long period of time. But eventually the lung cancer  

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:20.000
started to rise. And you could see the shape of the  

00:37:20.000 --> 00:37:24.000
curves are virtually identical. You can also see that the smoking  

00:37:24.000 --> 00:37:27.000
rate has dropped off a little bit in men, and actually has dropped off a  

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:31.000
little bit starting about 15 to 20 years ago with respect to  

00:37:31.000 --> 00:37:35.000
lung cancers as well. So smoking cessation has an effect.  

00:37:35.000 --> 00:37:39.000
If you reduce the exposure, you can reduce your risk.  

00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:44.000
That's true of men. Women have not caught up yet.  

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:48.000
Women started smoking later than men, about 20 years later,  

00:37:48.000 --> 00:37:53.000
and their lung cancer rates followed, then, their increases in cigarette  

00:37:53.000 --> 00:37:57.000
smoking with about a 20 year lag, and you can see now that lung cancer  

00:37:57.000 --> 00:38:02.000
among women is still rising. And it recently passed breast cancer  

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:08.000
as the most common type of cancer deaths among women.  

00:38:08.000 --> 00:38:13.000
So lung cancer is a major disease and is directly related to smoking  

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:19.000
and smoking history. Surprisingly, given that fact --  

00:38:19.000 --> 00:38:32.000
 -- still 47 million Americans smoke,  

00:38:32.000 --> 00:38:38.000
in recent polls something like 26% of men and 22% of women,  

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:44.000
a remarkably high number. And if you go to other countries,  

00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:50.000
the numbers are worse.  So the message clearly has not been  

00:38:50.000 --> 00:38:56.000
adequately delivered. But what is even more surprising to  

00:38:56.000 --> 00:39:02.000
me was the results of a survey done in 2002 where high school students  

00:39:02.000 --> 00:39:13.000
are asked whether they smoked.   

00:39:13.000 --> 00:39:18.000
What do you think? What percentage of American high  

00:39:18.000 --> 00:39:23.000
school students smoke? Anybody?  It was 28%; more than one  

00:39:23.000 --> 00:39:28.000
in four smoke. And I've heard recently that the  

00:39:28.000 --> 00:39:33.000
number is increasing since 2002. So, this very,  

00:39:33.000 --> 00:39:38.000
very detrimental agent which one controls oneself is clearly not  

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:42.000
going away and will lead to, unfortunately, the deaths of many of  

00:39:42.000 --> 00:39:47.000
these individuals because of lung cancer.  And by the way,  

00:39:47.000 --> 00:39:52.000
it's not just lung cancer that smoking is a problem for: emphysema,  

00:39:52.000 --> 00:39:56.000
heart disease, and other diseases as well.  I read a statistic which was  

00:39:56.000 --> 00:40:01.000
really shocking to me. Of that however many billions of  

00:40:01.000 --> 00:40:06.000
people are present on the planet today, the 500 million of them will  

00:40:06.000 --> 00:40:11.000
die early because of complications of cigarette smoking.  

00:40:11.000 --> 00:40:16.000
500 million people will live less than their full lifespans because of  

00:40:16.000 --> 00:40:22.000
cigarette smoke. So, if you learn nothing else from  

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:28.000
this class, if you currently smoke, stop.  And if you don't smoke, don't  

00:40:28.000 --> 00:40:33.000
start. OK, that was my little sermon.  

00:40:33.000 --> 00:40:39.000
Hopefully it had some effect.  And it provides a segue into --  

00:40:39.000 --> 00:40:48.000
 -- the sources of the mutations that  

00:40:48.000 --> 00:40:53.000
occur in genes during cancer progression.  We've just been  

00:40:53.000 --> 00:40:58.000
discussing exogenous, or environmental mutagens,  

00:40:58.000 --> 00:41:03.000
cigarette smoke being one, some lead exposure being another,  

00:41:03.000 --> 00:41:08.000
dietary carcinogens I mentioned, environmental pollutants like the  

